The paper discusses the application of Minority Games (MG) to solve distributed decision making problems in wireless networks. This topic falls under the category of Networked and Distributed Systems (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the theoretical aspects of MG, which falls under the category of Game Theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper discusses the self-organizing and autonomous nature of the network, which falls under the category of Self-Organizing Systems (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the use of MG to model and solve resource allocation problems, which falls under the category of Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA). Finally, the paper discusses the analysis of the problem of computation offloading in small cell networks, which falls under the category of Information Theory (cs.IT).
